{# Resolve the active locale and its chrome catalog.
   - `lang` comes from page front-matter (e.g. `lang: fr` on /index.fr.html).
     Untranslated pages have no `lang`, so they default to English.
   - `t` is the chrome catalog (nav labels, footer labels, UI strings).
     Available to this template AND every included partial via Nunjucks
     variable scoping. See src/_data/i18n.js for the full schema.
   - `status` (page front-matter, only set on .fr / .de pages) is either
     "beta" or "reviewed". Surfaced as a `data-i18n-status` attribute on
     <html> so the beta ribbon (src/_includes/beta-ribbon.njk) can render
     conditionally without a JS check. #}
{# `lang` arrives as a top-level front-matter variable on translated pages
   (e.g. `lang: fr` on /index.fr.html). Default to "en" when absent. Using
   `_lang` so we don't clobber the front-matter value via `set`. #}
{%- set _lang = lang or "en" -%}
{%- set t = i18n[_lang] -%}
{# Keep the `lang` variable usable downstream — make sure includes see
   the resolved value, not `undefined` on EN pages. #}
{%- set lang = _lang -%}
<!doctype html>
<html lang="{{ lang }}"{% if status %} data-i18n-status="{{ status }}"{% endif %}>
<head>
  <meta charset="utf-8">
  <meta http-equiv="X-UA-Compatible" content="IE=edge">
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1">

  <title>{% if title %}{{ title }} — {{ site.title }}{% else %}{{ site.fullName }}{% endif %}</title>
  <meta name="description" content="{{ description or site.description }}">

  {% if redirectTo %}
    <meta http-equiv="refresh" content="3;url={{ redirectTo }}">
    <link rel="canonical" href="{{ site.url }}{{ redirectTo }}">
    <meta name="robots" content="noindex,follow">
  {% else %}
    <link rel="canonical" href="{{ site.url }}{{ page.url }}">
  {% endif %}

  {# hreflang alternates. Only emitted when the page declares `alternates`
     in its front-matter — most pages currently don't, and that's fine
     (English-only pages don't need alternates). The shape is:
       alternates:
         en: /index.html
         fr: /index.fr.html
         de: /index.de.html  #}
  {% if alternates %}
    {%- for L in i18n._order -%}
      {% if alternates[L] %}<link rel="alternate" hreflang="{{ L }}" href="{{ site.url }}{{ alternates[L] }}">{% endif %}
    {%- endfor -%}
    <link rel="alternate" hreflang="x-default" href="{{ site.url }}{{ alternates.en or page.url }}">
  {% endif %}

  {# Favicon stack — SVG for modern browsers (any size, theme-tolerant),
     PNG fallbacks for legacy + iOS home-screen + Android PWA. Generated from
     src/assets/favicon.svg; sizes pinned to standard 32/16 (legacy),
     180 (apple-touch), 192+512 (Android PWA). #}
  <link rel="icon" href="/assets/favicon.svg" type="image/svg+xml">
  <link rel="icon" href="/assets/favicon-32x32.png" sizes="32x32" type="image/png">
  <link rel="icon" href="/assets/favicon-16x16.png" sizes="16x16" type="image/png">
  <link rel="apple-touch-icon" href="/assets/apple-touch-icon.png" sizes="180x180">
  <link rel="manifest" href="/assets/manifest.webmanifest">
  {# theme-color drives Android Chrome's address-bar tint + the iOS PWA
     status bar, so the browser chrome around the page matches the page
     itself. A media-scoped pair: the canonical EISS brand blue (sampled
     from the master PDF) in light mode, the dark page background
     (--bg = hsl(222 28% 7%)) in dark mode, so the chrome no longer
     reads light-blue over a dark page. Note: the `media` attribute
     tracks the OS colour scheme, not the site's manual theme toggle, so
     a visitor on a light OS who toggles the site to dark still gets the
     light tint — strictly better than the previous always-blue, never
     worse. A JS sync with the toggle is a possible follow-up. #}
  <meta name="theme-color" content="#007bc6" media="(prefers-color-scheme: light)">
  <meta name="theme-color" content="#0d1017" media="(prefers-color-scheme: dark)">

  {# Localised share card. The EN URL is `/assets/images/<slug>-meta.jpg`;
     translated variants live at `<slug>-meta.fr.jpg` / `<slug>-meta.de.jpg`,
     generated by scripts/make-share-cards.py. When the page's `lang` is
     not English we swap the suffix and trust the file exists — the script
     guarantees it for every (slug, lang) pair listed in its CARDS table.
     If a translated page somehow points at an English-only share card,
     the swap still happens and the og:image silently 404s; safer to
     ensure every translated page's slug appears in CARDS. #}
  {%- set rawMeta = metaImage or site.defaultMetaImage -%}
  {%- if lang != "en" and rawMeta -%}
    {%- set localisedMeta = rawMeta | replace("-meta.jpg", "-meta." + lang + ".jpg") -%}
  {%- else -%}
    {%- set localisedMeta = rawMeta -%}
  {%- endif -%}

  {# Open Graph (Facebook, LinkedIn, Mastodon, Bluesky preview cards) #}
  {#- Map the page language to a valid Open Graph locale (language_TERRITORY).
      A bare {{ lang|upper }} produced the invalid "en_EN"; English is en_GB. -#}
  {%- set ogLocale = {"en": "en_GB", "fr": "fr_FR", "de": "de_DE"}[lang] or "en_GB" -%}
  <meta property="og:type" content="website">
  <meta property="og:site_name" content="{{ site.title }}">
  <meta property="og:title" content="{{ title or site.fullName }}">
  <meta property="og:description" content="{{ description or site.description }}">
  <meta property="og:url" content="{{ site.url }}{{ redirectTo or page.url }}">
  <meta property="og:locale" content="{{ ogLocale }}">
  <meta property="og:image" content="{{ site.url }}{{ localisedMeta }}">
  <meta property="og:image:type" content="image/jpeg">
  <meta property="og:image:width" content="1200">
  <meta property="og:image:height" content="630">
  <meta property="og:image:alt" content="{{ title or site.fullName }}">

  {# Twitter / X Card #}
  <meta name="twitter:card" content="summary_large_image">
  <meta name="twitter:title" content="{{ title or site.fullName }}">
  <meta name="twitter:description" content="{{ description or site.description }}">
  <meta name="twitter:image" content="{{ site.url }}{{ localisedMeta }}">
  <meta name="twitter:image:alt" content="{{ title or site.fullName }}">
  {% if site.social.twitterHandle %}<meta name="twitter:site" content="{{ site.social.twitterHandle }}">{% endif %}

  {# JSON-LD Organization schema — gives Google the canonical signal
     it uses to attach a logo, name, and verified social profiles to
     the eiss-europa.com domain in the Knowledge Panel. Emitted on
     every page; search engines deduplicate.

     `logo` is now an ImageObject pointing at the high-res lockup PNG
     from the brand bundle (was a stale JPEG from the Mobirise era).
     Per Google's docs the logo image must be ≥60×60 with an aspect
     ratio between 1:1 and 4:1 — `logo-full-1024.png` is 1024×712
     (≈1.44:1), well within range, and carries the full identity
     (mark + EiSS + tagline) for the Knowledge Panel render.

     `foundingDate` ties the org to its 2017 inaugural conference
     at Panthéon-Assas — surfaces in the Knowledge Panel and helps
     disambiguate from other "EISS" acronyms. #}
  <script type="application/ld+json">
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "Organization",
    "name": "{{ site.fullName }}",
    "alternateName": "{{ site.title }}",
    "url": "{{ site.url }}/",
    "logo": {
      "@type": "ImageObject",
      "url": "{{ site.url }}/assets/images/brand/logo-full-1024.png",
      "width": 1024,
      "height": 712
    },
    "description": "{{ site.description }}",
    "email": "{{ site.contactEmail }}",
    "foundingDate": "2017",
    "sameAs": [
      "{{ site.social.twitter }}",
      "{{ site.social.linkedin }}",
      "{{ site.social.youtube }}"
    ]
  }
  </script>

  <script>
    // 1) Restore the user's chosen theme (light/dark) before paint to
    //    avoid a flash. 2) If the user has a language preference saved
    //    and they're landing on the English page but a translation
    //    exists, redirect to the translated version. Done in <head> so
    //    it fires before the body renders. Never auto-redirects AWAY
    //    from English unless an alternate is declared in the head —
    //    English is the unfailable fallback.
    (function(){
      try {
        var theme = localStorage.getItem('eiss-theme');
        if (theme === 'light' || theme === 'dark') {
          document.documentElement.setAttribute('data-theme', theme);
        }
      } catch(_) {}

      try {
        var saved = localStorage.getItem('eiss-lang');
        var current = document.documentElement.lang || 'en';
        if (saved && saved !== current && current === 'en' && saved !== 'en') {
          var alt = document.querySelector('link[rel="alternate"][hreflang="' + saved + '"]');
          if (alt && alt.href && alt.href !== location.href) {
            location.replace(alt.href);
          }
        }
      } catch(_) {}
    })();
  </script>

  {# Inter is self-hosted (see @font-face in site.css). Preload the Latin
     subset so first paint isn't delayed waiting on the stylesheet to
     discover the font. No Google Fonts request, so no third-party IP leak. #}
  <link rel="preload" href="/assets/fonts/inter/latin-wght-normal.woff2" as="font" type="font/woff2" crossorigin>
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="{{ '/assets/css/site.css' | bust }}">
</head>
<body>
  <a class="skip-link" href="#main">{{ t.skipLink }}</a>

  {# Sticky chrome wrapper. The ribbon (when present) + the nav stick
     together as one unit, so visitors keep both visible while
     scrolling. Previously only the nav stuck; the archive / beta
     ribbon scrolled out of view, which lost the disclaimer once the
     page got long. #}
  <div class="sticky-chrome" data-pagefind-ignore="all">
    {% if status == "beta" %}{% include "beta-ribbon.njk" %}{% endif %}
    {% if status == "archive" %}{% include "archive-ribbon.njk" %}{% endif %}
    {% include "nav.njk" %}
  </div>

  {# data-pagefind-body scopes the Pagefind index to page content (the
     chrome above/below is data-pagefind-ignore). REQUIRED: the bio-search
     stubs (search-bios.njk) carry data-pagefind-body, and Pagefind's rule
     is that once *any* page has it, pages *without* it are dropped from
     the index — so every real page must declare it here too, or only the
     stubs get indexed. See docs/search.md. #}
  <main id="main" role="main" data-pagefind-body>
    {{ content | safe }}
  </main>

  {% include "footer.njk" %}

  {# Site search. The modal is chrome (data-pagefind-ignore inside its own
     markup); search.js lazy-loads the deploy-time Pagefind index and
     degrades to an "unavailable" notice on local dev. The locale UI
     strings ride on a data-attribute so the no-framework JS can read them
     without a second i18n round-trip. #}
  {% include "search-modal.njk" %}
  <span data-search-strings='{"noResults":"{{ t.search.noResults }}","unavailable":"{{ t.search.unavailable }}","searching":"{{ t.search.searching }}"}' hidden></span>

  <script src="{{ '/assets/js/theme.js' | bust }}" defer></script>
  <script src="{{ '/assets/js/search.js' | bust }}" defer></script>
  <script>
    // Save the user's chosen language whenever they click any link
    // that carries an `hreflang` attribute. The two sources on the
    // site today are the language-switcher chips in the nav and the
    // "View English" link in the beta-translation ribbon. Treating
    // both the same way fixes the bug where a FR / DE visitor who
    // clicked the ribbon link landed on the EN page, got their saved
    // `eiss-lang=fr/de` preference re-applied by the in-head
    // redirect script, and bounced straight back to the translated
    // page. Issue #190.
    document.addEventListener('click', function(e) {
      var link = e.target.closest('a[hreflang]');
      if (link) {
        try { localStorage.setItem('eiss-lang', link.getAttribute('hreflang')); } catch(_) {}
      }
    });
  </script>
</body>
</html>
